        <p><!-- 
This edition is based on #Fleet_1888 (F) and #Thaplyal_1985 (Th) if different from Fleet, with occasional reference to Bhagwanlal Indraji's transcript (BI) in #ASIR_16 and to Sircar's Select Inscriptions (SI). 
--><lb n="1"/><milestone n="A" unit="column"/><gap precision="low" quantity="5" reason="illegible" unit="character"/> <supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->na</supplied><unclear cert="low">ma</unclear><unclear>ḥ</unclear><supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied> svasti śakti-ttrayopāt<unclear>t</unclear>a-jayaśavdān <unclear>m</unclear>ahā-nau-h<choice>
            <sic>ā</sic>
            <corr>a</corr>
          </choice>sty-a<milestone n="B" unit="column"/>śva-patti-sambhāra-durnivārāj jaya-skandhāvārā<unclear>T</unclear> <g type="mangala"/> gomatikoṭṭaka-samīpa-<unclear>vāsa</unclear><!-- 
L1. BI restores vāruṇavāsi-bhaṭṭārkāya (cited by Fleet as °bhaṭṭārakāya, which was probably BI's intent, since that is his reading in l13). As Fleet correctly notes, the lacuna is 5, at most 6 characters in size, so the restoration is impossible. SI suggests varuṇavāsine namaḥ, and also restores "siddham" at the start. 
--><!-- 
L1 and passim: F and BI transcribes śabdān, but as SI notes, the inscription does not distinguish between v and b, using v for both. In the subsequent text, F uses some b-s (but e.g. he prints vrāhmaṇottarān in l11), and BI uses b and v inconsistently. I agree with Sircar that there is no b in the inscription. 
--><!-- 
L1. The halanta T seems to be a tiny subscript character after rā. It is followed by a rather large ornamental character that I take to be a maṅgala symbol. BI transcribes it as śrī, while all other editors just ignore it (unless they read it as a halanta T, ignoring the little subscript thing - but this seems unlikely). The character has some resemblance to śr̥ (or better, gr̥), but it is not śrī, cf. e.g śrī-śrīmatyām in l2. It is probably not an alphabetic character. It looks somewhat like a mirrored S rotated 45 degrees counterclockwise, with a dot in the centre of the upper curve. 
--><!-- 
L1. vāsa at the end of the line is very faint compared to preceding characters. vā is almost clear, but sa is uncertain. 
--><lb break="no" n="2"/><milestone n="A" unit="column"/><supplied cert="low" reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->kāt</supplied> <gap precision="low" quantity="1" reason="illegible" unit="character"/> <supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->śrī-mādhavagupta</supplied><unclear>s tas</unclear>y<unclear>a</unclear> <supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->pu</supplied>t<supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->tra</supplied>s <unclear>tat-pā</unclear>dānu<unclear>dhy</unclear>ātaḥ
paramabhaṭ<unclear>ṭ</unclear>ārikā<milestone n="B" unit="column"/>yāṁ rā<unclear>jñyā</unclear>ṁ mahādevyāṁ śrī-śrīmatyām utpannaḥ paramabhāgavataḥ śrī-ādi<unclear>tya</unclear><supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->se</supplied><!-- 
L2. F prints a lacuna between the restored kāt and the restored śrī and notes that "Some sectarian title of Mādhavagupta must have been destroyed here; but there seems hardly room enough for paramabhāgavata or paramamāheśvara." BI tentatively restores paramabhaṭṭāraka. SI restores vāsakān mahārāja. In fact, if the basic assumptions are correct, there may be no further text lost at all in addition to "kāt śrī-mādhavagupta". Also, the restoration vāsakāt is in my opinion uncertain given that vāsa at the end of l1 is unclear, and there seems to be a semantic boundary after skandhāvārāt. 
--><!-- 
L2. BI reads sutas instead of puttras. The photo easily permits either. Since puttras is quite clear in l5 (though not before), I prefer puttras here too. 
--><!-- 
L2. Fleet prints gupta as clear; nothing of these characters is recognisable in the photo, though they may be cleared in Fleet's rubbing. I mark them up as restored, and add unclear markup wherever the photo is unclear. 
--><!-- 
L2. At the end of the line F prints tya as clear and se as unclear. In fact tya is faint though quite certain. No trace of se is visible, and I'm not at all certain the character was ever there; it may well have been in the next line. 
--><lb break="no" n="3"/><milestone n="A" unit="column"/><supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->na-devas tasya puttras ta</supplied><unclear cert="low">t-pā</unclear>dānu<unclear>dhyātaḥ</unclear> <unclear cert="low">pa</unclear><unclear>ra</unclear><unclear cert="low">mabhaṭṭā</unclear>rikāyāṁ rājñyāṁ
					<unclear>ma</unclear>hādevy<unclear>āṁ</unclear> <milestone n="B" unit="column"/>śrī-ko<space type="descender"/>ṇadevyām utpannaḥ parama-māheśvara-parama-bhaṭṭāraka-mahā<supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->rā</supplied><!-- 
L3. F only prints the ttra of puttras as unclear. I mark up restored and unclear according to what I can see in the photo. I'm also uncertain about whether or not any additional text was lost. Fleet assumes there wasn't any and I follow suit; actually, there may have been less text, e.g. deva may not have been part of the name; on the other hand, se may have been at the beginning of this line instead of the end of the previous line. 
--><!-- 
L3. BI's restoration has sutas instead of puttras. 
--><!-- 
L3. What's visible of the supposed characters "paramabhaṭṭā" doesn't seem to permit this reading. I follow F (who prints this as clear) because this is what one would expect. 
--><!-- 
L3. F prints the e of koṇadevyām as supplied (and SI prints the whole of de as supplied), but it is quite clear in the photo. 
--><!-- 
L3. F prints rājā at the end of l3, with only the ā-s as unclear. Nothing of these characters is visible in the photo, and I strongly doubt jā could have been there, so I restore it at the beginning of l4. rā too may have been in l4, and BI ends line 3 after mahā. 
--><lb break="no" n="4"/><milestone n="A" unit="column"/><supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->jādhirāja-parameśvara</supplied>-<unclear cert="low">śrī-devagupta-de</unclear>vas <unclear>tasya</unclear> <unclear cert="low">puttra</unclear>s <unclear>t</unclear>at-pād-ānudhyātaḥ <milestone n="B" unit="column"/>parama-bhaṭṭārikārikāyā<unclear>ṁ</unclear> rāj<unclear>ñ</unclear>yā<unclear>ṁ</unclear> mahādevyāṁ śrī-kama<unclear>la</unclear>devyām utpannaḥ parama-mā<unclear cert="low">he</unclear><!-- 
L4. It is far from certain that the restored text fills the lacuna; a couple of characters more or less would easily be possible. I accept śrī-devagupta as a (very tentative) reading rather than a restoration, since BI prints it (as clear), and Fleet notes that it "is very indistinct; but I agree with Bhagwanlal Indraji that it can be read with sufficient certainty." Nothing of it is recognisable in the photo. 
--><!-- 
L4. As before, BI reads sutas instead of F's puttras. 
--><!-- 
L4. For F's kamala, BI reads kumāra. Fleet asserts that the reading is "distinctly kamala". I mark up la as unclear (it looks rather different from clear instances of l later on). ku is out of the question, and mā is unlikely. 
--><lb break="no" n="5"/><milestone n="A" unit="column"/><supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->śvara-parama-bhaṭṭāraka-mahā</supplied>r<unclear>ā</unclear><unclear cert="low">jā</unclear><supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->dhi</supplied>rā<unclear>ja</unclear>-p<unclear>ara</unclear>m<unclear>eś</unclear>vara-śr<unclear>ī</unclear>-v<unclear>i</unclear>ṣ<unclear>ṇ</unclear>ugu<unclear>pt</unclear>a-devas ta<milestone n="B" unit="column"/>sya
put<unclear>tr</unclear>as tat-pādānudhyātaḥ parama-bhaṭṭārikāyā<unclear>ṁ</unclear> rājñyāṁ mahādevyāṁ
śrī Ijjāde<!-- 
L5. At the beginning of the line, F prints hārājā as clear, dhi as unclear (or restored?) and everything afterward as clear. BI also prints parama as clear. The surface of the stone does not seem to have peeled off in that region, but there are no discernible characters in the photo. 
--><!-- 
L5. At the end of l5 Fleet prints vyā as unclear (meant to be restored?). Indraji, contrarily, does not even read de here. Actually, de is clear; I don't think there is enough space for vyā and there is certainly no discernible trace of it. 
--><lb break="no" n="6"/><milestone n="A" unit="column"/><supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->vyām utpannaḥ pa</supplied>ra<supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->ma</supplied><supplied cert="low" reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->māheśvara</supplied>-<unclear>pa</unclear><supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->rama</supplied><unclear cert="low">bhaṭṭāraka</unclear>-<unclear>mahārā</unclear><unclear cert="low">jā</unclear><unclear>dh</unclear>irāja-parameśva<milestone n="B" unit="column"/>ra-śrī-<unclear>j</unclear><unclear cert="low">ī</unclear>vitagupta-deva<supplied reason="omitted">ḥ</supplied>
kuśalī nagara-bh<unclear>u</unclear>k<unclear>t</unclear>au vālavī-vai<unclear>ṣa</unclear>yika-śrī-v<choice>
            <unclear>ā</unclear>
            <unclear>o</unclear>
          </choice><!-- 
L6. At the beginning of the line, F prints everything before bhaṭṭāraka as unclear, with only dots for māheśvara, with a note to the effect that "Either bhāgavata or māheśvara is illegible here." BI actually reads paramabhāgavataḥ here. I prefer to restore māheśvaraḥ (tentatively) because that's what Devagupta was above. (SI too prefers to restore māheśvaraḥ, but also mentions bhāgavataḥ as possible) Clear/unclear/restored markup as per the photo. 
--><!-- 
L6. For jīvitagupta, BI reads savitr̥gupta. Fleet says the reading is "distinctly jīvita", and this is also Cunningham's reading (in his commentary accompanying Indraji's transliteration, #ASIR_16:68). In the photo, jī is far from clear, but sa seems even less likely. 
--><!-- 
L6. The l of kuśalī is strange, it has an additional curved stroke below the left-hand side. 
--><lb break="no" n="7"/><milestone n="A" unit="column"/><gap precision="low" quantity="20" reason="illegible" unit="character"/> <unclear>pa</unclear><unclear cert="low">dra</unclear><unclear>li</unclear>k<unclear>ā</unclear>ntaṣpāti-vā<milestone n="B" unit="column"/>ruṇikā-grā<unclear>ma</unclear>-g<unclear>o</unclear><unclear cert="low">care ke</unclear>la-<unclear>tala</unclear>-<unclear cert="low">vā</unclear><unclear>ṭaka-tala</unclear>-sīm<unclear>ā</unclear>-ka<unclear>rm</unclear><unclear cert="low">m</unclear>a-<unclear cert="low">tada</unclear>-ma<unclear>hā</unclear><!-- 
L7. I accept Fleet's tentative reading of padralikā, but these characters are very uncertain. Indraji only reads ...likā; SI tentatively suggests paṭṭolikā. 
--><!-- 
L7. I'd be tempted to read fp instead of ṣp. The reason I do not (and, probably, why F and BI did not, though SI prints upadhmānīya) is that ṣ is full sized at regular height, with a smaller subscript p. To qualify as upadhmānīya, I'd expect the character to be superscript and smaller. Still, the use of ṣp here is probably a vestigial upadhmānīya, i.e. it's not a phonemic but a graphemic peculiarity. 
--><!-- 
L7. F prints the ā of vāruṇikā as supplied. I feel it is definitely there, but it's an extension of the top to the right (with a vertical serif at the end), whereas most other ās in the inscription go upward from the top. 
--><!-- 
L7. F: grāma-goṣṭh(ā)(?na)-kula-talāvāṭaka-dūta-sīmakarmakara-ma(?dyā). BI: grāmā gā ... la-talavāṭaka-dūta-sīmākarmakara-mahā. (SI follows F, except in emending vāṭaka to vāṭake and reading madyā at the end.) My reading is tentative at best and serves mainly to show where I find Fleet's readings untenable. In particular: goṣṭhāna seems impossible. The character after go (which may be gā) actually looks rather like ja; the next one looks like pe; reading gocare is a desperate attempt to make sense of it. F's dūta also seems impossible even though it's also BI's reading; the sequence kata is almost clear. (Did F and BI read my ka as dū and see another ka before that?) At the end, F's madyā is not impossible, but BI's mahā is much more likely. Cf also the very similar sequence in l19. 
--><lb break="no" n="8"/><milestone n="A" unit="column"/> <gap precision="low" quantity="18" reason="illegible" unit="character"/> <supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->rājā</supplied><unclear>n</unclear>aka-rājaputtra-<milestone n="B" unit="column"/>rā<unclear>jā</unclear>mat<unclear>t</unclear>ra-mahā-<unclear cert="low">kārttā</unclear><unclear>kr̥</unclear>tika-<unclear>mahā-da</unclear>ṇ<unclear>ḍa</unclear>nāyaka-mahāprat<unclear>īhā</unclear>ra-ma<unclear>hā</unclear>sā<!-- 
L8. F and BI read taka at the beginning of the legible bit. Sircar proposes to read naka, as the end of rājānaka which frequently precedes rājaputra. I find this very likely. SI goes on to restore ...samupāgatān sarvvān eva rāja-rājānaka, which may be correct, but is only a conjecture. 
--><!-- 
L8. All editors emend rājāmattra to rājāmātya. I wonder; couldn't the title be rājamātra? Also, the characters themselves are not entirely clear; in particular, jā seems uncertain: if there is an ā mātrā to that character, it is attached to the top prong, while jā would normally have the ā extending upward from the middle prong (compare ijjāde at the end of l5). 
--><!-- 
L8. F reads mahā...kṣatika, BI only mahā...ka. The reading mahākārttākr̥tika is from Sircar who thinks "there can hardly be any doubt" about it and refers to the Monghyr plate of Devapāla for a parallel. 
--><lb break="no" n="9"/><milestone n="A" unit="column"/><supplied cert="low" reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->manta</supplied> <gap precision="low" quantity="10" reason="illegible" unit="character"/> <unclear>p</unclear>ramāt<unclear cert="low">r̥</unclear>-sa<unclear cert="low">ra</unclear>-<supplied cert="low" reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->bhaṅga</supplied>-<unclear cert="low">k</unclear><supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->u</supplied><unclear>mā</unclear>rāmātya-rā<milestone n="B" unit="column"/>jas<unclear>thānī</unclear>yopari<unclear>ka</unclear> <gap precision="low" quantity="3" reason="illegible" unit="character"/> <unclear>d</unclear><supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->āśāpa</supplied><unclear>r</unclear><supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->ā</supplied>dhi<unclear>ka</unclear>-cauroddhara<unclear cert="low">ṇ</unclear>i<unclear cert="low">ka</unclear>-d<unclear cert="low">āṇ</unclear>ḍ<unclear cert="low">i</unclear>ka-da<unclear cert="low">ṇḍa</unclear><!-- 
L9. BI tentatively restores ndhivigrahika at the beginning of the line, then reads nothing before (ku)mārāmātya. F does not restore the beginning, and reads (?pra)mātasā in the lacuna. SI restores manta-mahā-dauḥsādhasādhanika-pramātr̥sarabhaṅga, again on the basis of the Monghyr plate. I partially adopt his restoration. 
--><!-- 
L9. dāśāparādhika is Sircar's restoration (from the Monghyr plate), F reads only dhika. SI does not note that d and r are actually more or less visible in the photograph; BI actually reads da (though not ra) in the lacuna. 
--><lb break="no" n="10"/><milestone n="A" unit="column"/><supplied cert="low" reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->pāśika</supplied> <gap precision="low" quantity="6" reason="illegible" unit="character"/> <supplied cert="low" reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->tad-āyuktaka-viniyukta</supplied>ka-<supplied cert="low" reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->hasty-aśvo</supplied><unclear>ṣṭ</unclear><unclear cert="low">r</unclear><unclear>a</unclear>-vala-<milestone n="B" unit="column"/>vyāp<supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->r̥</supplied>ta-kiś<unclear>o</unclear>ra-vaḍav<unclear>ā-g</unclear><supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->o</supplied>-mahi<supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->ṣ</supplied><unclear>y-a</unclear><supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->dh</supplied><unclear cert="low">ikr̥</unclear>ta-d<supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->ū</supplied>ta-<unclear cert="low">p</unclear>r<supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->ai</supplied><unclear cert="low">ṣa</unclear><unclear>ṇi</unclear>ka-gam<unclear>āga</unclear>m<unclear>an</unclear>ika-A<!-- 
L10. I adopt all of Sircar's restorations from the Monghyr plate. F restores only pāśika, then reads ### ka ### (?rṣṇi)vala-vyāyata-ki(?śo)ra(?vāṭaka)-g(r)āma-h ### d #t ### vaṇikaga ### pati-ka(?rma). BI reads ### ka ### barmmavala vyāhataki śūravaṭaka grāma(?sta) # tadatra vāruṇika grāma-ma-ka(?rma). The Monghyr plate, as cited by SI, has the initial part letter for letter up to vyāpr̥ta, reading vyāpr̥taka. The bit corresponding to the latter part is kiśora-vaḍavā-go-mahiṣāvikādhyakṣa-dūtapraiṣaṇika-gamāgamika; go-mahiṣādhikr̥ta occurs in the Nalanda plate of Devapāla. I diverge from Sircar in only one detail: he reads gamāgamika here (as per the Monghyr plate), but that is impossible. The correct reading is probably gamāgamanika (my manika corresponding to Fleet's patika and BI's mamaka), though the n is unclear. 
--><lb break="no" n="11"/><milestone n="A" unit="column"/><supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->bhitvaramāṇa-viṣaya</supplied><unclear cert="low">pati-</unclear><supplied cert="low" reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->cāṭa-bhaṭa</supplied> <gap precision="low" quantity="1" reason="illegible" unit="character"/> <unclear cert="low">ra</unclear> <gap precision="low" quantity="1" reason="illegible" unit="character"/> s<unclear>e</unclear><unclear cert="low">va</unclear>k<supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->ā</supplied><unclear>d</unclear><supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->īn anyāṁś cākīrtti</supplied>tās<unclear>m</unclear>at-pā<milestone n="B" unit="column"/>da-pras<unclear>ā</unclear>dopa<unclear>jī</unclear>vina<unclear cert="low">ś ca</unclear> <unclear>prati</unclear><unclear cert="low">vā</unclear>sinaś ca vrāhmaṇottarā<unclear cert="low">n</unclear> mahattara-ku<add place="below">ṭ<unclear>u</unclear></add>mvi-pur<unclear>o</unclear><!-- 
L11. At the beginning, I again adopt SI's restorations from the Monghyr plate, which reads abhitvaramāṇa-viṣayapati after gamāgamika. The restoration cāṭa-bhaṭa is from "similar passages of other early inscriptions" and is thus more uncertain. F reads nothing in the lacuna except rasaka, which probably corresponds to the sa and ka of Sircar's sevakādīn, plus a trace that may indeed be an r, one or two characters before this sa. 
--><!-- 
L11. For the second part of the first panel, I again follow Sircar's restoration (based on "similar passages of other early inscriptions"), except that he supplies a "na" to read "kīrttitān asmat." There is absolutely no trace of any engraving between tā and sma, and though the space is a bit more than normal between characters, it's rather narrow for an additional character. So I think the original reading was kīrttitāsmat. (Sircar may have meant the additional na as the correction of an omission, not as supplying lost text - but it isn't really necessary.) F reads ###tāsmat, and BI reads ### dhyāsitāsmat. 
--><!-- 
